## Due to the unfavorable disease situation were ordered  Extraordinary veterinary measures to all farms of the company

## The company owns farms in 3 regions

- all persons, including employees, who have entered another poultry facility in the past 48 hours are prohibited from entering the premises of the holding where poultry is kept. With the exception of private and official veterinarian;
- all farms were tested for avian influenza. In breeding duck farms, testing is carried out at regular intervals.
- keeping records of all activities carried out by the breeder's employees or other persons who have also entered other poultry facilities, including other facilities of the breeder (for example vaccinations, veterinary procedures);
- securing poultry houses against the entry of unauthorized persons and the entry of wild birds;
- equipping the entrances and exits to all poultry houses with appropriate equipment with an effective disinfectant for disinfecting shoes, using them and permanently maintaining them in an effective condition;
- cleaning and disinfecting all vehicles entering or leaving the facility;
- keeping records of persons and vehicles entering and leaving the facility and submitting them to the regional veterinary authority (RVA) for inspection upon request;
- immediately report to the relevant RVA an increase in mortality, a decrease in laying eggs, or other clinical signs of disease in farmed poultry;
- use all equipment used in the collection and transport of hatching eggs only if they are cleaned and disinfected after each use.

<!-- image -->

## Possible causes of the spread of the disease

- shared service staff (maintenance and repairs, vaccination team, etc.)
- short distance between farms
- movements of staff between farms cannot be ruled out (despite the ban on such movements)
- insufficient protection of straw bedding stocks from wild birds

A direct link between the outbreaks (path of spread) has not yet been proven, the above-mentioned paths are being considered. There is increased official supervision in all of the owner's farms.

<!-- image -->

## Number of killed animals in HPAI poultry outbreaks in 2026 (1 - 8)

- a total of 89,995 breeding ducks had to be killed with a total weight of 318,800 kg.
- on the Egg Production Enterprise farm, 236,500 laying hens with a total weight of 336,530 kg were culled.

